<UL><h3>Link to the General Social Survey</h3>
<a href="http://www.icpsr.umich.edu/GSS/index.html">GSS</a></UL>


<!--a

<p><UL>I have found the GSS to be an excellent source of data for
examples, and you may find it useful to generate data for your
project.  You can see the codebook of all the questions they ask by
clicking on one of the items under "Codebook Indexes" on the homepage
(e.g., Mnemonic).  Clicking on the name of the variable in the
mnemonic list shows marginal distributions of the responses in many
years.  Dr. Brett Presnell of the Statistics Department at UF has
prepared a useful document that shows how to download data from the
GSS and then put it in a SAS program for analysis (e.g., to form
contingency tables or to do logistic regression modeling).  See the
pdf file on <a
href="http://web.stat.ufl.edu/~presnell/Teaching/sta4504-2000sp/">Downloading
and using data from the General Social Survey</a> in the Handouts
section of his webpage for this course. </UL>

</a--> 


<p><h3>Links about software</h3>

<p>A website I've created for my more advanced book <a
href="http://www.stat.ufl.edu/~aa/cda/cda.html"><I>Categorical Data
Analysis</I></a> (2nd edition, Wiley 2002) has details about various
software for conducting categorical data analysis. <p>

<p> 
<UL><h3>SAS:</h3> 

<p>SAS is available in all the <a
href="http://labs.circa.ufl.edu/cse.html">CIRCA labs</a>, such as CSE
211.  You can get SAS for your home PC with a one-year license through
the <a href="http://www.software.ufl.edu/sas/">Student Home-Use
Program</a>.  A license costs about $40 but is free to renew for as
many years as you are at UF, and apparently a certain number of
licences are free every year from UF's Software Licensing Services
(from the UF Bookstore on a first come first serve basis).
Alternatively, graduate students can get a grove account
(www.grove.ufl.edu). This is a free account for grad students and
allows access to such software as SAS
(http://grove.ufl.edu/applications.shtml).

<p>The CIRCA handout <a
href="http://www.circa.ufl.edu/handouts/windows/sas.html">"SAS for
Windows"</a> is useful for getting started.  It can also be helpful to
use a primer such as "The Little SAS Book: A Primer" by L. Delwiche
and S. Slaughter or "SAS System for Elementary Statistical Analysis"
by S. Schlotzhauer and R. Littell.
  
<p>The SAS/STAT User's Guide contains more detailed information.  See
<a href="http://docs.stat.ufl.edu/sasdoc/stat/index.htm">SAS/STAT
guide</a>.  A link to SAS manuals is <a
href="http://software.ufl.edu/sashtml/main.htm">SAS Manuals</a>.
There you can find all the detail you need about PROCs we use in this
course, such as PROC GENMOD, PROC LOGISTIC, and PROC FREQ.
</UL>
<p>



<p> <UL><h3>SPSS:</h3> A student version of SPSS is available at the
Technology Hub for about $75.  You can get it more cheaply for your
home PC with a one-year license through the <a
href="http://www.software.ufl.edu/spss/">Student Home-Use Program</a>
</UL>
<p>

<p> 
<UL><h3>R and S-Plus:</h3> R is free software, popular among
statisticians because of its power and flexibility but harder to learn
to use.  It is an open source version of S-Plus, and many S-Plus
functions also work in R.  For details, see the <a
href="http://www.r-project.org/"> R web site </a>.  This includes a
link to manuals, such as "An Introduction to R", and to the archives
in the Comprehensive R Archive Network (CRAN).

For other useful information and links about R and S-Plus, see the
homepage of the UF professor <a
href="http://web.stat.ufl.edu/~presnell/">Dr.  Brett Presnell</a>.
Dr. Presnell also has a page on <a
href="http://web.stat.ufl.edu/~presnell/Teaching/sta4504-2000sp/R/"> R
for Categorical Data Analysis </a> from when he taught STA 4504-5503
that has many examples of the use of R.  Some of these are for data
sets in the text for this course.  </UL>
<p>

<p><h3>Exams</h3> Here is a <a href="sample-test.pdf">sample of the
types of questions</a> (pdf file) you will see on Exam 1.  There will
be a combination of true-false or multiple-choice questions as well as
problems.  A couple of the problems are likely to come directly from
the homework exercises.  The problems put main emphasis on
interpretation, rather than calculation.  A formula page is attached
to the back of the exam so you do not feel it necessary to memorize
formulas.  Here is a <a href="sample-test2.pdf">sample of the types of
questions</a> (pdf file) you will see on Exam 2.  Here is a <a
href="sample-test3.pdf">sample of the types of questions</a> (pdf
file) you will see on Exam 3.

